com.cyc.kb

Interface KbObject.KbObjectWithArity

  • All Superinterfaces:
    KbObject
    All Known Subinterfaces:
    Assertion, BinaryPredicate, Context, Fact, FirstOrderCollection, KbCollection, KbFunction, KbIndividual, KbPredicate, KbTerm, Relation, Rule, SecondOrderCollection, Sentence
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    AssertionWrapper, BinaryPredicateWrapper, ContextWrapper, FactWrapper, FirstOrderCollectionWrapper, KbCollectionWrapper, KbFunctionWrapper, KbIndividualWrapper, KbPredicateWrapper, KbTermWrapper, RelationWrapper, RuleWrapper, SecondOrderCollectionWrapper, SentenceWrapper
    Enclosing interface:
    KbObject

    public static interface KbObject.KbObjectWithArity
extends KbObject
    A KbObject which may potentially be non-atomic; ie., a Sentence, an Assertion, or a functional KbTerm. Because a constant has no "arguments", an atomic KbTerm will have a formula arity of 0.

    • Method Detail

      • getArity

        Integer getArity()
        Returns the syntactic arity of this object. If it has a getRelation applied to some arguments (i.e. it's a Sentence, an Assertion, or a functional term), the arity is the number of arguments. By convention, Cyc constants have a formula arity of 0.
        Returns:
        the arity of this object, null if not a Cyc constant, functional term, Sentence, or Assertion

      • getArgument

        <O> O getArgument(int argPosition)
           throws KbTypeException,
                  CreateException,
                  UnsupportedOperationException
        Gets the object in argPosition argument position of this KbObject as an object of type O. This method works for Sentences and Assertions, as well as non-atomic KbTerms. However, because a constant has no "arguments", calling this method on a KbObject representing a Cyc constant will result in a KbException.
        Type Parameters:
        O - the object type
        Parameters:
        argPosition - the argument position of the object returned
        Returns:
        the object at getPos as a O
        Throws:
        CreateException
        KbTypeException
        UnsupportedOperationException - if getArgument is called on Atomic terms. Do not use this to test for term atomicity, use KbObject.isAtomic() instead.
